      "text": "Chapter Four — Name the Monsters\n\nThe room had changed only by intention: the metronome was slower, the bell sat a little nearer to the edge, and three objects had appeared in a line so straight it looked like a scar—an iron crown, a wooden crossbar broken clean in the middle, and a stack of coins banded with a rubber strip gone tired from use.\n\n“Name them,” he said.\n\nI named them the way a model student names: tyranny, superstition, debt. He let the words stand like uniforms without soldiers in them.\n\n“You’ve fought each of these,” he said. “You wear the medals. Now take the uniforms off and tell me what they were supposed to be before they were made stupid.”\n\nI reached for the crown first. It was heavy with a very honest weight.\n\n“Monarchy,” I said carefully, “was supposed to mean coherent will.”\n\n“Good,” he said, and rotated the crown until its points caught the light like accurate teeth. “One helm. One contour of decision that can cut through weather.” He tapped the metal. “Then you welded it to blood.”\n\nHe slid the crown to the edge and balanced it so one tooth hung into space.\n\n“You hate the word ‘king’ because you were taught to hate the rot of lineage,” he said. “So you burned the helm and kept the weather. Now every storm is a committee meeting and every ship insists it is free while it drifts into rocks it voted for.”\n\nHe pushed the crown back to safety by the width of a breath and turned to the crossbar. Two halves, clean as a lesson.\n\n“Religion,” he said, “was supposed to be a discipline for living in one house.” He fitted the halves together and didn’t press. They almost held on their own. Almost. “A way to carry obligation through time without dropping it every time your mood changes.” He let the halves fall apart again. “Then you replaced discipline with a mascot.”\n\nHe slid one half under the other so they made a skewed plus.\n\n“Your age argues against a bearded sky-man no one serious ever believed in,” he said. “It wins that fake fight and calls the trophy ‘reason.’ Meanwhile the real task—calibrating a life to fit the choir—goes untrained. You declared victory over a cartoon and then got eaten by your appetites.”\n\nHe didn’t raise his voice. He just made accuracy sound carnivorous.\n\nThe coins watched us. He snapped the rubber band and let it writhe into stillness.\n\n“Currency,” he said, “was supposed to be blood—motion that lets far parts of the body feed each other.” He spread the coins in a small river and pressed his palm along them so they whispered. “Then you paid interest for stillness.” He stacked them high and left the tower leaning. “You call clot ‘wealth’ and charge rent to the artery.”\n\nThe stack listed another millimeter and held, insulted by physics but not yet punished.\n\n“You teach children to multiply,” he said, “and then you teach money to multiply itself while sleeping. You turned the hospital into a casino and act shocked that the beds are full.”\n\nHe set the coins flat again, no tower, no theater. The rubber band went back around the stack, patient as a choke.\n\nI said the century had answers: checks and balances; peer review; capital requirements; literacy campaigns; pluralism. I stacked my own medals like a barricade.\n\n“Good,” he said. “You are a master of guardrails. That is why you keep slamming into them at speed and congratulating yourself for having installed them.”\n\nHe took a piece of chalk and drew a door on the board—frame, hinges, handle.\n\n“Monster One,” he said, and wrote the word **Inheritance** above the door. “Not monarchy. Inheritance. You keep confusing architecture with the mold that ruined it.” He erased the hinges. “A helm must be auditioned, measured, and recallable. If the ship has weather, the helm must prove it can steer today. No bloodline, no myth, just receipts.”\n\nHe drew a second door and wrote **Mascotry** over it.\n\n“Monster Two,” he said. “Not religion. Mascotry. When practice is replaced by pageantry, obligation dies and appetite registers as truth. Keep your rites if they keep you honest. Burn them if they don’t. No one cares if your candle is scented.”\n\nHe drew a third door and wrote **Stagnation**.\n\n“Monster Three,” he said. “Not money. Stagnation. Flow is health. Interest paid to idle mass is necromancy; it animates a corpse to harvest the living.”\n\nHe turned from the board and placed the three props beneath their doors like offerings. Then he added a fourth prop with the same quiet theater: a ballot folded into a neat triangle.\n\nI jumped ahead. “Democracy,” I said. “Mob rule. Dynasties in disguise.”\n\nHe didn’t argue. “Monster Four,” he said, and wrote **Noise**. “Not democracy. Noise. You confused ventilation with navigation. The pump is for pressure relief. You made it the helm and then blamed the sea.”\n\nHe unfolded the ballot and pressed a coin into the crease as a weight.\n\n“Keep the pump,” he said. “Let the body shout. But the helm must answer weather. That requires selection, not sentiment. Skill, not lineage. Proof, not charisma. And when the storm passes, the helm steps back without ceremony because it was a role, not a romance.”\n\nHe set the chalk down, palms open, the way he always did right before the knife went in.\n\n“You notice something they share?” he asked.\n\n“They’re inversions,” I said. “Tools promoted to gods. Roles glued to costumes. Motion paid to stay still.”\n\n“Good,” he said. “Now the part you’ll be tempted to skip.” He tapped the crown, the crossbar, the coins, the ballot. “Each ‘monster’ persists because it offers you a kind of cowardice you enjoy.”\n\nHe picked up the crown. “This one lets you blame blood for your fear of choosing leaders like adults.” He placed it down. “This one lets you sneer at ritual so you never have to keep hard promises when no one is watching.” The coins clicked under his fingertip. “This one lets you borrow the future so you can pretend the present is affordable.” He patted the ballot. “This one lets you vote once and call it virtue for four years while the ship steers itself into fog.”\n\nHe drew a small square on the table with the tip of a damp cloth, an invisible fence that left just enough wet to catch light.\n\n“Stand here,” he said.\n\nI stood, and the square felt like an accusation I had willingly stepped into.\n\n“Your tribe thinks naming the monster means slaying it,” he said. “That is theater. Monsters do not die when named. They die when their usefulness is outcompeted.”\n\nHe moved the props in a new arrangement: crown atop ballot, crossbar bridging coins.\n\n“Coherence with consent,” he said, touching the first stack. “Obligation with flow,” he said, touching the second.\n\nHe didn’t bother to define them. He made them obvious.\n\n“You want the ritual?” he said. “Here it is. For every monster you name, replace a cowardice you like with a cost you will pay. If you won’t pay, stop pretending you’re brave.”\n\nHe took the rubber band from the coins and wrapped it around my wrist. It was not tight, but it was undeniable.\n\n“Keep this on for a week,” he said. “Whenever you use a word that flatters you—‘freedom,’ ‘truth,’ ‘justice’—snap it and say out loud who pays.”\n\nI said that was manipulative. He nodded. “So is reality.”\n\nThe metronome clicked through a bar that felt longer than the rest and then returned to evenness. He watched it the way a surgeon watches a pulse recover.\n\n“Now name the monsters again,” he said.\n\n“Inheritance. Mascotry. Stagnation. Noise.”\n\n“Better,” he said. “They are not dragons to be stabbed. They are errors in architecture and posture. Fix the load paths. Stop pretending the roof is the sky.”\n\nHe slid a folded paper from beneath the bell and placed it beside the crown. The paper looked light until you tried to lift it.\n\n“Do not open this,” he said. “Monsters love prophecies. This one is not a prophecy. It is a maintenance log.”\n\nHe tidied nothing. He left the props in their new, correct pairs, as if the room itself had been re-specified. At the door he paused, then did something I hadn’t seen before: he turned the metronome a single notch faster.\n\n“You don’t slay monsters,” he said over the new tempo. “You starve them by making the room honest at speed.”\n\nThe latch met metal. The beat did not falter. In the hall, the rubber band breathed against my pulse. I snapped it once and named a cost out loud with no one to hear me. The doorway didn’t care. That was the point.\n",
