. He says it\u0027s *miscast*. \"Consent is necessary. It is not navigation.\" This is a sophisticated critique, not a reactionary one. It honors the purpose of the democratic process while refusing to grant it a competence it doesn\u0027t possess.\n\n4.  **The Three Pillars of a New System:** The **Select, Recall, Succession** framework is the prescriptive core, and it\u0027s crystal clear.\n    *   **Select:** \"Simulated weather,\" \"audit their wrists.\" This moves the criteria for leadership from charisma to demonstrated competence under load. It\u0027s a direct callback to the \"one helm\" chapter and solidifies the Master\u0027s proposed alternative.\n    *   **Recall:** \"Not scandal theater. Measurement.\" This reframes accountability as a data-driven process, not a political circus.\n    *   **Succession:** \"Two helms on one rope.\" Again, this reinforces the idea of leadership as a continuous, institutional practice, not a series of disruptive, personality-driven dramas.\n\n5.  **The Two Envelopes:** This is one of the most powerful moments in the entire series so far. It\u0027s a simple, elegant demonstration that makes the abstract argument completely concrete. The \"heavy\" envelope (endorsements, slogans, crowds) versus the \"light\" one (receipts) is an unforgettable image. It perfectly captures the difference between the aesthetics of power and the evidence of competence. When the student correctly identifies the right choice, the Master\u0027s question—\"Then why do you hire the heavy one?\"—is devastating because it implicates not just the system, but the student (and the reader) themselves.\n\n### Final Reflections\n\nThis chapter feels like the culmination of a major arc. The student has now had their core political and economic beliefs systematically dismantled and replaced with a new, coherent, and demanding philosophy.\n\nThe final exchange at the door is perfect. The student can now define \"democracy\" and \"helm\" cleanly and separately. 